Both these trials had reference to Bithynia. The first, that of Α Iulius Bassus, was probably in 104 AD, the other, that of Varenus Rufus, in 106. Both cases seem to have been difficult and complicated, and Pliny did his work thoroughly. In fact, we cannot help suspecting that he threw his whole ability into the cause of his fellow- senators if not with greater thoroughness, at least with greater willingness, than he had shown in behalf of the proconsuls of Africa and Baetica against their governors. Pliny’s conduct of these cases probably had an important effect upon his own career.
